Definition 6.1. Let $F$ be an endofunctor on a category $\mathcal{M}$. The extension of $F$ over $\mathcal{M}^{C}$ away from a subset $J\subseteq C$ is the endofunctor on $\mathcal{M}^{C}$, which we keep denoting by $F$, given by $F\mathbf{X}=(F_{c}X(c))_{c\in C}$ where $F_{c}$ is the identity functor if $c\in J$ and $F_{c}=F$ if $c\not\in J$. If $F$ is equipped with an augmentation $\eta$, then $(\eta_{\mathbf{X}})_{c}=\eta_{X(c)}$ if $c\not\in J$ and the identity map otherwise. Similarly, if $F$ is equipped with a coaugmentation $\varepsilon$, then $(\varepsilon_{\mathbf{X}})_{c}=\varepsilon_{X(c)}$ if $c\not\in J$ and the identity map otherwise.
Definition 3.14. For each $H\in\mathfrak{F}$, define the left group action: $\alpha_{\scriptscriptstyle H}:\Gamma\times\mathrm{Mor}(E(\{e\}),E(H))% \rightarrow\mathrm{Mor}(E(\{e\}),E(H)):(\theta,\varphi)\mapsto\varphi\circ\theta.$ Let $\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}$ be the stabilizer of $\varphi_{\scriptscriptstyle H}$ under this action. Let $\mathfrak{F}$ be the family of subgroups of $\Gamma$ that contains all the stabilizers $\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}$.
Definition 1.4. Let $E/K$ be a finite Galois extension of fields and suppose $\mathcal{F}$ is a collection of intermediate fields. Denote $G=\mathrm{Gal}(E/K)$ and define the family of subgroups $\mathfrak{F}=\{H\subseteq G\;|\;E^{H}=F\mbox{ for some }F\in\mathcal{F}\}$. The $n$-th Bredon-Galois cohomology of $E/K$ for the family $\mathcal{F}$ is by definition $\mathrm{H}^{n}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,\underline{E}^{\times})$.
Definition 3.6. Let $M$ be a $\mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak{F}}G$-module and let $\mathfrak{M}$ be the category associated to $\{M(G/H)\}_{H\in\mathfrak{F}}$. We denote by $\mathrm{Ext}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)$ the set of equivalence classes of abelian right extensions of $\mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak{F}}G$ by $\mathfrak{M}$, such that induced the $\mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak{F}}G$-module structure on $M$ by the extensions is the given one. A representative of an element in $\mathrm{Ext}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)$ is then called an abelian right extension of $\mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak{F}}G$ by $M$.
Definition 5.10. Two splittings $s$ and $t$ of the standard split $\mathfrak{F}$-structure on $(G,M)$ are said to be $M$-conjugate if there exists an element $m\in M$ such that $s(x)=mt(x)m^{\scriptscriptstyle-1}$ for all $x\in G$. The notion of $M$-conjugacy places an equivalence relation on the set of all splittings.
Definition 1.1. Let $0\rightarrow M\rightarrow\Gamma\xrightarrow{\pi}G\rightarrow 1$, be an abelian group extension of $G$ by $M$. An $\mathfrak{F}$-structure on this extension is a collection of subgroups $\{\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}\}_{H\in\mathfrak{F}}$ of $\Gamma$, such that (i) for each $H\in\mathfrak{F}$, $\pi:\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}\xrightarrow{\cong}H$; (ii) for each $H,K\in\mathfrak{F}$ and $x\in G$, if $x^{\scriptscriptstyle-1}Hx\subseteq K$ then there exists $y\in\pi^{\scriptscriptstyle-1}(x)$ such that $y^{\scriptscriptstyle-1}\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}y\subseteq\Gamma_{% \scriptscriptstyle K}$. This $\mathfrak{F}$-structure $\{\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}\}_{H\in\mathfrak{F}}$ is called split if there exists a group homomorphism $s:G\rightarrow\Gamma$ such that $\pi\circ s=id$ and for each $H\in\mathfrak{F}$, the subgroups $s(H)$ and $\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}$ are conjugate in $\Gamma$ by $m_{\scriptscriptstyle H}$ for some $m_{\scriptscriptstyle H}\in M$. Two splittings $s$ and $t$ of an $\mathfrak{F}$-structure on $(G,M)$ are said to be $M$-conjugate if there exists an element $m\in M$ such that $s(x)$ and $t(x)$ are conjugate by $m$ for all $x\in G$. An $\mathfrak{F}$-structure on $(G,M)$ is just an $\mathfrak{F}$-structure on some extension of $G$ by $M$. We define a notion of equivalence of $\mathfrak{F}$-structures and denote the set of equivalence classes of $\mathfrak{F}$-structures on $(G,M)$ by $\mathrm{Str}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)$ (see 3.9).
Definition 3.1. An abelian right extension of $\mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak{F}}G$ by $\mathfrak{M}$ consists of a category $\mathfrak{E}$ with objects $\{E(H)\}_{H\in\mathfrak{F}}$ and functors: $\mathfrak{M}\xrightarrow{i}\mathfrak{E}\xrightarrow{\pi}\mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak% {F}}G$ satisfying the following properties. (i) $i(M(G/H))=E(H)$ and $\pi(E(H))=G/H$ for all $H\in\mathfrak{F}$; (ii) $\forall H\in\mathfrak{F},\forall\bar{m}_{\scriptscriptstyle H},\bar{n}_{% \scriptscriptstyle H}\in\mathrm{Mor}({M}(G/H),{M}(G/H))$, if $i(\bar{m}_{\scriptscriptstyle H})=i(\bar{n}_{\scriptscriptstyle H})$, then $\bar{m}_{\scriptscriptstyle H}=\bar{n}_{\scriptscriptstyle H}$, i.e. $i$ is injective on morphisms; (iii) $\forall H,K\in\mathfrak{F},\forall\varphi\in\mathrm{Mor}(G/H,G/K)$, there exists a $\theta\in\mathrm{Mor}(E(H),E(K))$ such that $\pi(\theta)=\varphi$, i.e. $\pi$ is surjective on morphisms; (iv) $\pi(i(\bar{m}_{\scriptscriptstyle H}))=id$ for all $H\in\mathfrak{F}$ and for all $\bar{m}_{\scriptscriptstyle H}\in\mathrm{Mor}(M(G/H),M(G/H))$; (v) $\forall H,K\in\mathfrak{F},\forall\varphi_{1},\varphi_{2}\in\mathrm{Mor}({E}(H% ),{E}(K))$: if $\pi(\varphi_{1})=\pi(\varphi_{2})$, then there exists a unique $\bar{m}_{\scriptscriptstyle H}\in\mathrm{Mor}(M(G/H),M(G/H))$ such that $\varphi_{1}\circ i(\bar{m}_{\scriptscriptstyle H})=\varphi_{2}$.
Definition 5.1. An $\mathfrak{F}$-derivation of $G$ into $M$ is a map of $\mathfrak{F}$-sets $\mathcal{D}:\Delta^{1}\rightarrow\mathfrak{F}(M)$ such that: $\forall H,H_{1},H_{2}\in\mathfrak{F},\forall x_{1}H_{1}\in(G/H_{1})^{% \scriptscriptstyle H},\forall x_{2}H_{2}\in(G/H_{2})^{H_{1}}$: $\mathcal{D}_{\scriptscriptstyle H}(x_{1}x_{2}H_{2})=M(x_{1}H_{1})\Big{(}% \mathcal{D}_{H_{1}}(x_{2}H_{2})\Big{)}+\mathcal{D}_{\scriptscriptstyle H}(x_{1% }H_{1}).$ The set of all $\mathfrak{F}$-derivations of $G$ into $M$ forms an abelian group which we denote by $\mathrm{Der}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)$. Given an element $m=(m_{\scriptscriptstyle H})_{H\in\mathfrak{F}}\in\prod_{H\in\mathfrak{F}}M(G/H)$, the principal $\mathfrak{F}$-derivation $\mathcal{D}_{m}$ of $G$ into $M$ is a map of $\mathfrak{F}$-sets $\mathcal{D}:\Delta^{1}\rightarrow\mathfrak{F}(M)$ defined as follows: $\forall H,K\in\mathfrak{F},\forall xK\in(G/K)^{\scriptscriptstyle H}$: $(\mathcal{D}_{m})_{\scriptscriptstyle H}(xK)=M(xK)(m_{\scriptscriptstyle K})-m% _{\scriptscriptstyle H}.$ The set of all principal $\mathfrak{F}$-derivation of $G$ into $M$ forms an abelian subgroup of $\mathrm{Der}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)$ which we denote by $\mathrm{PDer}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)$.
Definition 6.10. Let $k\in\mathbb{N}\cup\{\infty\}$. We say that an extension of fields $E/K$ is $k$-admissible if it is a finite Galois extension with Galois group $G$ such that for every $\sigma\in G\setminus\{e\}$, there exist at least $k$ discrete valuations $\pi$ of $E$ such that $G_{\pi}=\langle\sigma\rangle$ and such that $\pi|{{}_{K}}$ is unramified in $E$.
Definition 4.3. Define the cochain complex: $0\rightarrow C^{0}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)\xrightarrow{d^{0}}C^{1}_{\mathfrak{F}}(% G,M)\rightarrow\ldots\rightarrow C^{n}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)\xrightarrow{d^{n}}C% ^{n+1}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)\rightarrow\ldots$ by $C^{n}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)=\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathfrak{F}\mbox{-set}}(\Delta^{n},% \mathfrak{F}(M))$ for each $n$ and $d^{n}:C^{n}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)\rightarrow C^{n+1}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M):f% \mapsto d^{n}(f),$ with $\displaystyle d^{n}(f)_{\scriptscriptstyle H}(\varphi_{1},\ldots,\varphi_{n+1})$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle M(\varphi_{1})\Big{(}f_{\scriptscriptstyle{H_{1}}}(\varphi_{2},% \ldots,\varphi_{n+1})\Big{)}$ $\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}f_{\scriptscriptstyle H}(\varphi_{1},% \ldots,\varphi_{i+1}\circ\varphi_{i},\ldots,\varphi_{n+1})$ $\displaystyle+(-1)^{n+1}f_{\scriptscriptstyle H}(\varphi_{1},\ldots,\varphi_{n})$ where $(\varphi_{1},\ldots,\varphi_{n+1})\in\mathrm{Mor}(G/H,G/H_{1},\ldots,G/H_{n+1})$.
Definition 3.7. An abelian right extension $\mathfrak{M}\xrightarrow{i}\mathfrak{E}\xrightarrow{\pi}\mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak% {F}}G$ is called split if there exists a functor $s:\mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak{F}}G\rightarrow\mathfrak{E}$ such that $\pi\circ s=id$.
Definition 5.8. Two splittings $s$ and $t$ of the extension: $\mathfrak{M}\xrightarrow{i}\mathfrak{M}\rtimes\mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak{F}}G% \xrightarrow{\pi}\mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak{F}}G$ are said to be $M$-conjugate if there exists an element $m=(m_{\scriptscriptstyle H})_{H\in\mathfrak{F}}\in\prod_{H\in\mathfrak{F}}M(G/H)$ such that $s(\varphi)\circ i(\bar{m}_{\scriptscriptstyle H})=i(\bar{m}_{% \scriptscriptstyle K})\circ t(\varphi)$ for all $H,K\in\mathfrak{F}$, for all $\varphi\in\mathrm{Mor}(G/H,G/K)$. The notion of $M$-conjugacy places an equivalence relation on the set of all splittings.
Definition 3.3. The abelian right $\mathfrak{M}$-extensions, $\mathfrak{M}\xrightarrow{i_{1}}\mathfrak{E}_{1}\xrightarrow{\pi_{1}}\mathcal{O% }_{\mathfrak{F}}G$ and $\mathfrak{M}\xrightarrow{i_{2}}\mathfrak{E}_{2}\xrightarrow{\pi_{2}}\mathcal{O% }_{\mathfrak{F}}G$, are called equivalent if there exists a functor $\theta:\mathfrak{E}_{1}\rightarrow\mathfrak{E}_{2}$ such that the following diagram commutes: $\xymatrix{\mathfrak{M}\ar[r]^{i_{1}}\ar[d]^{id}&\mathfrak{E}_{1}\ar[r]^{\pi_{1% }}\ar[d]^{\theta}&\mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak{F}}G\ar[d]^{id}\\ \mathfrak{M}\ar[r]^{i_{2}}&\mathfrak{E}_{2}\ar[r]^{\pi_{2}}&\mathcal{O}_{% \mathfrak{F}}G.}$ It is not difficult to check that this implies $\theta({E}_{1}(H))={E}_{2}(H)$ for all $H\in\mathfrak{F}$ and that $\theta$ is bijective on morphisms.
Definition 5.3. Suppose $M\in G\mbox{-mod}$. Given an element $m\in M$, a principal derivation $D_{m}$ of $G$ into $M$ is a set map $D:G\rightarrow M$ defined as follows: for all $x\in G$: $D_{m}(x)=x\cdot m-m.$ An $\mathfrak{F}$-derivation of $G$ into $M$ is a set map $D:G\rightarrow M$ such that: for all $x,y\in G$: $D(xy)=x\cdot D(y)+D(x)$ and $D|{{}_{\scriptscriptstyle H}}:H\rightarrow M$ is a principal derivation $D_{m_{\scriptscriptstyle H}}:H\to M$, for each $H\in\mathfrak{F}$. Note that $m_{\scriptscriptstyle H}$ depends on $H$ and that the set of all $\mathfrak{F}$-derivations of $G$ into $M$ forms an abelian group which we denote by $\mathrm{Der}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)$. The set of all principal derivations of $G$ into $M$ forms an abelian subgroup of $\mathrm{Der}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)$ which we denote by $\mathrm{PDer}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)$.
Definition 1.7. Let $k\in\mathbb{N}\cup\{\infty\}$. We say that an extension of fields $E/K$ is $k$-admissible if it is a finite Galois extension with Galois group $G$ such that for every nontrivial $\sigma\in G$, there exist at least $k$ discrete valuations $\pi$ of $E$ such that $G_{\pi}=\langle\sigma\rangle$ and $\pi|_{K}$ is unramified in $E$.
Definition 3.9. An $\mathfrak{F}$-structure on (1) is a collection of subgroups $\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}$ of $\Gamma$ for each $H\in\mathfrak{F}$, such that: (i) for each $H\in\mathfrak{F}$, $\pi:\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}\xrightarrow{\cong}H$; (ii) for each $H,K\in\mathfrak{F}$ and $x\in G$, if $x^{\scriptscriptstyle-1}Hx\subseteq K$, then there exists $y\in\pi^{\scriptscriptstyle-1}(x)$ such that $y^{\scriptscriptstyle-1}\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}y\subseteq\Gamma_{% \scriptscriptstyle K}$. This collection of subgroups of $\Gamma$ is also denoted by $\mathfrak{F}$. It readily follows that $\Gamma_{\{e\}}=\{e\}$, $\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}\cap M=\{e\}$ and that $\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}$ commutes with $M^{\scriptscriptstyle H}$ for each $H\in\mathfrak{F}$. Now, let us suppose we have another group extension: $0\rightarrow M\rightarrow\Gamma^{\prime}\xrightarrow{\pi^{\prime}}G\rightarrow 1.$ The $\mathfrak{F}$-structures $\{\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}\}_{H\in\mathfrak{F}}$ on $(\ref{eq: group extension})$ and $\{\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}^{\prime}\}_{H\in\mathfrak{F}}$ on $(\ref{eq: group extension2})$ are called equivalent if and only if there exists a group homomorphism $\theta:\Gamma\rightarrow\Gamma^{\prime}$ such that $\xymatrix{0\ar[r]&M\ar[r]\ar[d]^{id}&\Gamma\ar[r]^{\pi}\ar[d]^{\theta}&G\ar[d]% ^{id}\ar[r]&1\\ 0\ar[r]&M\ar[r]&\Gamma^{\prime}\ar[r]^{\pi^{\prime}}&G\ar[r]&1}$ commutes and such that for each $H\in\mathfrak{F}$, $\theta(\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H})=m_{\scriptscriptstyle H}^{% \scriptscriptstyle-1}\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}^{\prime}m_{% \scriptscriptstyle H}$ for some $m_{\scriptscriptstyle H}\in M$ (note that $m_{\scriptscriptstyle H}$ depends on $H$). It is clear that, in this case, $\theta$ is an isomorphism and $(\ref{eq: group extension})$ is equivalent with $(\ref{eq: group extension2})$ in the usual sense of group extension. An $\mathfrak{F}$-structure $\{\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H}\}_{H\in\mathfrak{F}}$ on $(\ref{eq: group extension})$ is called split if there exists a group homomorphism $s:G\rightarrow\Gamma$ such that $\pi\circ s=id$ and such that for each $H\in\mathfrak{F}$, $s(H)=m_{\scriptscriptstyle H}^{\scriptscriptstyle-1}\Gamma_{\scriptscriptstyle H% }m_{\scriptscriptstyle H}$ for some $m_{\scriptscriptstyle H}\in M$ ($m_{\scriptscriptstyle H}$ depends on $H$). This implies that $(\ref{eq: group extension})$ is split extension in the usual sense. Note that, in general, a split extension of $G$ by $M$ can have a non-split $\mathfrak{F}$-structure. An $\mathfrak{F}$-structure on $(G,M)$ is just an $\mathfrak{F}$-structure on some abelian extension of $G$ by $M$. By $\mathrm{Str}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,M)$, we denote the set of all equivalence classes of $\mathfrak{F}$-structures on $(G,M)$.
Definition 5.1. Let $\mathfrak{X}$ be a class of groups. ${\scriptstyle\bf H}^{\mathfrak{F}}\mathfrak{X}$ is defined as the smallest class of groups containing the class $\mathfrak{X}$ with the property that if a group $G$ acts cellularly on a finite dimensional CW-complex $X$ with all isotropy subgroups in ${\scriptstyle\bf H}^{\mathfrak{F}}\mathfrak{X}$ and such that for each subgroup $F\in\mathfrak{F}\cap G$ the fixed point set $X^{F}$ is contractible, then $G$ is in ${\scriptstyle\bf H}^{\mathfrak{F}}\mathfrak{X}$.
Definition 6.6. A group $G$ has periodic $\mathfrak{F}$-Bredon cohomology with period $q>0$ after $k$ steps, if the functors $\mathrm{H}^{n}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,-)$ and $\mathrm{H}^{n+q}_{\mathfrak{F}}(G,-)$ are naturally equivalent for all $n>k$.
Definition 1.1. Let $\mathfrak{F}$ be a class of groups closed under taking subgroups and let $G$ be a group. We set $\mathfrak{F}\cap G=\{H\leq G\;|\;\mbox{$H$ is isomorphic to a subgroup in $% \mathfrak{F}$}\}.$ Let $\mathfrak{X}$ be a class of groups. Then ${\scriptstyle\bf H}^{\mathfrak{F}}\mathfrak{X}$ is defined as the smallest class of groups containing the class $\mathfrak{X}$ with the property that if a group $G$ acts cellularly on a finite dimensional CW-complex $X$ with all isotropy subgroups in ${\scriptstyle\bf H}^{\mathfrak{F}}\mathfrak{X}$ and such that for each subgroup $F\in\mathfrak{F}\cap G$ the fixed point set $X^{F}$ is contractible, then $G$ is in ${\scriptstyle\bf H}^{\mathfrak{F}}\mathfrak{X}$. ${{\scriptstyle\mathrm{L}\bf H}}^{\mathfrak{F}}\mathfrak{X}$ is defined to be the class of groups that are locally ${\scriptstyle\bf H}^{\mathfrak{F}}\mathfrak{X}$-groups.
Definition 6.1. A discrete group $G$ has jump $\mathfrak{F}$-Bredon (co)homology if there exists an integer $k\geq 0$, such that for each subgroup $H$ of $G$ we have $hd_{\mathfrak{F}\cap H}(H)=\infty$ ($cd_{\mathfrak{F}\cap H}(H)=\infty$) or $hd_{\mathfrak{F}\cap H}(H)\leq k$ ($cd_{\mathfrak{F}\cap H}(H)\leq k$). The minimum of all such $k$ is called jump height and denoted $hjh_{\mathfrak{F}}(G)$ ($cjh_{\mathfrak{F}}(G)$).
Definition 1.2 (2-couniversality) Given two 2-categories ${\mathbb{A}}$, ${\mathbb{B}}$, a 2-functor $L:{\mathbb{A}}\to{\mathbb{B}}$ and an object $B$ of ${\mathbb{B}}$, we say an object $Q$ of ${\mathbb{A}}$ is $L$-2-couniversal (briefly $L$-couniversal) over $B$ if there exists a 2-natural isomorphism between 2-functors $K:{\rm Hom}_{{\mathbb{B}}}(-,B)\circ L\to{\rm Hom}_{{\mathbb{A}}}(-,Q).$
Definition \thedfn. Assume $S$ is a semigroup. We call $D\subseteq S$ diagonal if $s,t\in S\quad\text{and}\quad sd,d,dt\in D\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad sdt\in D.$
Definition \thedfn. Let $S$ be a semigroup. We call $N\subseteq S$ (bi/tri)normal if $\displaystyle s\in S$ $\displaystyle\Rightarrow\qquad sN=Ns.$ $\displaystyle s,t\in S\ \text{ and }\ st\in N$ $\displaystyle\Rightarrow\qquad sNt\subseteq N.$ $\displaystyle s,t\in S\ \text{ and }\ tsn=nts=n,st\in N$ $\displaystyle\Rightarrow\qquad snt\in N.$
Definition \thedfn. If $\pi:C\rightarrow G$ is a Hausdorff locally injective ringoid bundle and $G=\pi[C^{\times}]$ is an ample groupoid then we call $\pi$ a Steinberg bundle.4Note $G=\pi[C^{\times}]$ can be viewed as a strong form of saturation in the sense of [Kum98], i.e. $\pi^{-1}\{gh\}=\pi^{-1}\{g\}\pi^{-1}\{h\}$, for all $g,h\in G$.
Definition \thedfn. We call $a\in\mathrm{ran}(\Phi)$ well-supported if $0=\inf\{\rho(a,q):q<r\in\mathrm{ran}(\Phi)\text{ and $r$ supports }a\}.$
Definition \thedfn. We call $B\subseteq S$ bistable if, for all $s,t\in S$, $st\in B\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad s\Phi(t),\Phi(s)t\in B.$ We call $\Phi$ bistable when $\mathrm{ran}(\Phi)$ is bistable.
Definition \thedfn. A bundle is a continuous open surjection $\pi:C\rightarrow G$ between topological spaces $C$ and $G$. We call $\pi$ a category bundle if, moreover, (1) $C$ is a topological category, (2) $G$ is an étale groupoid, and (3) $\pi$ is an isocofibration.
Definition \thedfn. Given sets $S$ and $A$ with $S\subseteq A$, we say $S$ acts on $A$ if we have an associative product from $S\times A\cup A\times S$ to $A$, i.e. for all $s,t\in S$ and $a\in A$, $(st)a=s(ta),\quad(sa)t=s(at)\quad\text{and}\quad(as)t=a(st).$
Definition \thedfn. For any $U\subseteq S$, we define $\rho_{U}:A\times A\rightarrow\mathbb{R}_{+}$ by $\rho_{U}(a,b)=\inf\{\rho(\Phi(au^{\prime})u,\Phi(bu^{\prime})u)):U\ni t<_{u^{% \prime}}u\}.$
Definition \thedfn. Assume $S$ acts on $A\supseteq S$. We call $\Phi:A\rightarrow S$ an expectation if, $\displaystyle\Phi(\Phi(a))$ $\displaystyle=\Phi(a)\quad\text{and}$ $\displaystyle\Phi(a)\Phi(b)$ $\displaystyle=\Phi(\Phi(a)b)=\Phi(a\Phi(b)),$ for all $a,b\in A$. We call $\Phi$ shiftable if, for all $a\in A$ and $s\in S$, $\displaystyle\Phi(sa)s$ $\displaystyle=s\Phi(as).$
Definition \thedfn. We call $\pi:C\rightarrow G$ a ringoid bundle if it is both a zero category bundle and an abelian group bundle such products distribute over sums, i.e. $(a+b)c=ab+ac\qquad\text{and}\qquad c(d+e)=cd+ce,$ for all $a,b,c,d,e\in C$ with $\pi(a)=\pi(b)$, $\mathsf{s}(b)=\mathsf{r}(c)$, $\mathsf{s}(c)=\mathsf{r}(d)$ and $\pi(d)=\pi(e)$.
Definition \thedfn. We call a metric $\rho$ on a semigroup $S$ absolute if, for all $s,t\in S$, $|\|s\|-\|t\||\leq\rho(s,t).$
Definition \thedfn. A Steinberg ring is a structure $(A,S,Z,\Phi)$ where (1) $A=\Sigma S$ is a ring with subsemigroup $S=\raisebox{1.075pt}{\scalebox{0.8}{$\bigoplus$}}S=S^{>}$. (2) $\Phi:A\rightarrow S$ is a non-degenerate additive bistable shiftable expectation. (3) $Z=\raisebox{1.075pt}{\scalebox{0.8}{$\bigoplus$}}Z\subseteq\mathsf{I}(\mathsf{% Z}(\mathrm{ran}(\Phi)))$ is subtractive, bistable and binormal. (4) Every $a\in\mathrm{ran}(\Phi)$ is well-supported (w.r.t. the discrete metric $\rho$), i.e. we have $r\in\mathrm{ran}(\Phi)$ which both supports and dominates $a$.
Definition \thedfn. We say $s\in S$ supports $a\in A$ if $0\neq\inf\{\rho(0,\Phi(as^{\prime})s):0\neq t<_{s^{\prime}}s\}.$
