Definition 2.4. The centre of a $({\mathcal{C}},{\mathcal{C}})$-bimodule category ${\mathcal{M}}$ is a category ${\mathcal{Z}}_{\mathcal{C}}({\mathcal{M}})$ the objects of which are given by pairs $(M,\tau)$, where $M$ is an object in ${\mathcal{M}}$ and $\tau_{X}:M\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}% }}} }X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\simeq}}{{\ \longrightarrow\ }}X\mbox{ \scalebox{% 0.75}{\char pzd}}M$ are isomorphisms natural in $X$ such that the hexagon diagram $\xymatrix{&X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}(M\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{% \rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }Z)\ar@{<-}[r]_{\vartheta_{% \scriptscriptstyle X,M,Z}}\ar[ld]_{{\rm id}_{X}\otimes\,\tau_{Z}\ \ \ }&(X% \mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M)\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{% \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }Z\ar@{<-}[rd]^{\ \ \tau_{X}\otimes\,{\rm id}_{Z% }}&\\ X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}(Z\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M)\ar@{% <-}[rd]_{\phi_{\scriptscriptstyle X,Z,M}\quad}&&&(M\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{% \rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }X)\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{% \rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }Z\ar@{<-}[ld]^{\quad\psi_{M,% X,Z}}\\ &(X\otimes Z)\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M\ar@{<-}[r]_{\tau_{X\otimes Z}% }&M\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }(X% \otimes Z)&}$ commutes for all $M\in{\mathcal{M}}$ and $X,Z\in{\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 2.1. A left module category over ${\mathcal{C}}$ is a category ${\mathcal{M}}$ equipped with a bifunctor $\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}:{\mathcal{C}}\times{\mathcal{M}}\to{% \mathcal{M}}$ and natural isomorphisms, again called associativity and unit constraint, $\phi_{\scriptscriptstyle X,Y,M}:(X\otimes Y)\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}% M\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\simeq}}{{\longrightarrow}}X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{% \char pzd}}(Y\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M),{\quad\quad\quad}1_{% \scriptscriptstyle M}:\mathbb{1}\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle\simeq}}{{\longrightarrow}}M$ for all $X,Y\in{\mathcal{C}}$ and $M\in{\mathcal{M}}$, such that the customary pentagon and triangle diagrams $\xymatrix{&((X\otimes Y)\otimes Z)\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M\ar[ld]_{% \alpha_{X,Y,Z}\otimes\,{\rm id}_{M}\quad\ \ }\ar[rd]^{\ \ \phi_{% \scriptscriptstyle X\otimes Y,Z,M}}&\\ (X\otimes(Y\otimes Z))\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M\ar[d]_{\phi_{% \scriptscriptstyle X,Y\otimes Z,M}}&&(X\otimes Y)\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd% }}(Z\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M)\ar[d]^{\phi_{\scriptscriptstyle X,Y,Z% {\scalebox{0.7}{\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}}M}}\\ {\quad\quad\quad}X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}((Y\otimes Z)\mbox{ % \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M)\ar[rr]^{{\rm id}_{X}\otimes\,\phi_{% \scriptscriptstyle Y,Z,M}}&&X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}(Y\mbox{ % \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}(Z\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M)){\quad\quad% \quad}}$ and $\xymatrix{(X\otimes\mathbb{1})\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M\ar[rr]^{\phi% _{\scriptscriptstyle X,\mathbb{1},M}}\ar[rd]_{r_{X}\otimes\,{\rm id}_{M}\quad}% &&X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}(\mathbb{1}\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd% }}M)\ar[ld]^{\quad{\rm id}_{X}\otimes\,l_{M}}\\ &X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M&}$ commute.
Definition 3.6. An anti Yetter-Drinfel’d (aYD) contramodule $M$ over a left Hopf algebroid $(U,A)$ is a left $U$-module (with action denoted by juxtaposition) being at the same time a right $U$-contramodule (with contraaction $\gamma$) such that both underlying $A$-bimodule structures (3.2) and (3.20) coincide, i.e., $a\smalltriangleright m\smalltriangleleft b=amb,\qquad m\in M,\ a,b\in A,$ and such that contraaction followed by action results in $u(\gamma(f))=\gamma\big{(}u_{+(2)}f(u_{-}\raisebox{1.0pt}{${\scriptstyle({-})}% $}u_{+(1)})\big{)},\qquad\forall u\in U,\ f\in\operatorname{Hom}_{% \scriptscriptstyle{{A^{\rm op}}}}(U,M).$ If action followed by contraaction results in the identity, i.e., for all $m\in M$ $\gamma(\raisebox{1.0pt}{${\scriptstyle({-})}$}m)=m$ holds, then $M$ is called stable, where $\raisebox{1.0pt}{${\scriptstyle({-})}$}m\colon u\mapsto um$ as a map in $\operatorname{Hom}_{\scriptscriptstyle{{A^{\rm op}}}}(U,M)$.
Definition 4.6. For two left $U$-comodules $N,M$ over a left bialgebroid $(U,A)$ which is left Hopf and with $U_{\smalltriangleleft}$ projective over $A$, the $A$-bimodule $\operatorname{HOM}^{\ell}(N,M)=\{g\in\operatorname{Hom}^{\scriptscriptstyle{U}% }(N,M\otimes_{\scriptscriptstyle{A}}{}_{{\smalltriangleright}}{U}\,)\mid% \lambda^{\ell}g\in\mathrm{im}(\jmath)\}$ is called the space of (left) rational morphisms from $N$ to $M$.
Definition 3.5. A right contramodule over a left bialgebroid $(U,A)$ is a right $A$-module $M$ together with a right $A$-module map $\gamma:\operatorname{Hom}_{\scriptscriptstyle{{A^{\rm op}}}}(U_{% \smalltriangleleft},M)\to M,$ usually termed the contraaction, subject to the diagram $\begin{split}&\displaystyle\xymatrix{\operatorname{Hom}_{\scriptscriptstyle{{A% ^{\rm op}}}}(U,\operatorname{Hom}_{\scriptscriptstyle{{A^{\rm op}}}}(U,M))\ar[% rrr]^{-}{\scriptstyle{\operatorname{Hom}_{\scriptscriptstyle{{A^{\rm op}}}}(U,% \gamma)}}\ar[d]_{-}{\simeq}\hfil&&&\displaystyle\operatorname{Hom}_{% \scriptscriptstyle{{A^{\rm op}}}}(U,M)\ar[d]^{-}{\gamma}\\ \displaystyle\operatorname{Hom}_{\scriptscriptstyle{{A^{\rm op}}}}(U_{% \smalltriangleleft}\otimes_{\scriptscriptstyle{A}}{}_{{\smalltriangleright}}{U% }\,,M)\ar[rr]_{-}{\scriptstyle{\operatorname{Hom}_{\scriptscriptstyle{{A^{\rm op% }}}}(\Delta_{\ell},M)}}&&\displaystyle\operatorname{Hom}_{\scriptscriptstyle{{% A^{\rm op}}}}(U,M)\ar[r]_{-}{\gamma}&\displaystyle M\end{split}}$ which we will refer to as contraassociativity, as well as $\begin{split}&\displaystyle\xymatrix{\operatorname{Hom}_{\scriptscriptstyle{{A% ^{\rm op}}}}(A,M)\ar[rr]^{-}{\operatorname{Hom}_{\scriptscriptstyle{{A^{\rm op% }}}}(\varepsilon,M)}\ar[dr]_{-}{\simeq}\hfil&&\displaystyle\operatorname{Hom}_% {\scriptscriptstyle{{A^{\rm op}}}}(U,M)\ar[dl]^{-}{\gamma}\\ &\displaystyle M&\end{split}}$ to which we refer as contraunitality.
Definition 4.3. For a right $U$-comodule $P$ and a left $U$-comodule $M$ over a left bialgebroid $(U,A)$ with $U_{\smalltriangleleft}$ projective over $A$, the $A$-bimodule $\operatorname{HOM}^{r}(P,M):=\{f\in\operatorname{Hom}_{\scriptscriptstyle{{A^{% \rm op}}}}(P,M)\mid\lambda^{r}f\in\mathrm{im}(\jmath)\}$ is called the space of (right) rational morphisms from $P$ to $M$.
Definition 2.6. A trace functor consists of a functor $T:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{E}}$ between a (unital, associative) monoidal category $({\mathcal{C}},\otimes,\mathbb{1})$ and a category ${\mathcal{E}}$, together with a family of isomorphisms ${\rm tr}_{\scriptscriptstyle X,Y}:T(X\otimes Y)\simeq T(Y\otimes X)$ for all $X,Y\in{\mathcal{C}}$ that is unital (by which we mean ${\rm tr}_{\scriptscriptstyle\mathbb{1},Y}={\rm id}$), functorial in $X$ and $Y$, as well as fulfils the property ${\rm tr}_{\scriptscriptstyle Z,X\otimes Y}\circ{\rm tr}_{\scriptscriptstyle Y,% Z\otimes X}\circ{\rm tr}_{\scriptscriptstyle X,Y\otimes Z}={\rm id}$ for all $X,Y,Z\in{\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 2.2. A bimodule category over two monoidal categories ${\mathcal{C}}$ and ${\mathcal{D}}$ is a category ${\mathcal{M}}$ that is simultaneously a left ${\mathcal{C}}$-module and right ${\mathcal{D}}$-module category with respective associative constraints $\phi$ and $\psi$, plus middle associativity constraints given by natural transformations $\vartheta_{\scriptscriptstyle X,M,Z}:(X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M)% \mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }Z% \stackrel{{\scriptstyle\simeq}}{{\ \longrightarrow\ }}X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{% \char pzd}}(M\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd% }}}} }Z)$ for $M\in{\mathcal{M}}$, $X\in{\mathcal{C}}$, and $Z\in{\mathcal{D}}$, such that the two pentagon diagrams $\xymatrix{&((X\otimes Y)\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M)\mbox{\raisebox{5.% 0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }Z\ar[ld]_{\phi_{% \scriptscriptstyle X,Y,M}\otimes\,{\rm id}_{Z}\quad\ \ }\ar[rd]^{\ \ \vartheta% _{\scriptscriptstyle X\otimes Y,M,Z}}&\\ (X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}(Y\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M))% \mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }Z\ar[% d]_{\vartheta_{\scriptscriptstyle X,Y{\scalebox{0.7}{\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{% \char pzd}}}}M,Z}}&&(X\otimes Y)\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}(M\mbox{% \raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }Z)\ar[d]^{% \phi_{\scriptscriptstyle X,Y,M{\raisebox{-0.2pt}{\scalebox{0.7}{\mbox{% \raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }}}}Z}}\\ {\quad\quad\quad}X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}((Y\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{% \char pzd}}M)\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd% }}}} }Z)\ar[rr]^{{\rm id}_{X}\otimes\,\vartheta_{\scriptscriptstyle Y,M,Z}}&&X% \mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}(Y\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}(M\mbox{% \raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }Z)){\quad% \quad\quad}}$ and $\xymatrix{&X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}(M\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{% \rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }(W\otimes Z))\ar[ld]_{{\rm id% }_{X}\otimes\,\psi_{M,W,Z}\quad\ \ \ }\ar@{<-}[rd]^{\ \ \ \vartheta_{% \scriptscriptstyle X,M,W\otimes Z}}&\\ X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}((M\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}% {{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }W)\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{% \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }Z)\ar@{<-}[d]_{\vartheta_{\scriptscriptstyle X,% M{\scalebox{0.7}{\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{% \char pzd}}}} }}}W,Z}}&&(X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}M)\mbox{\raisebox{% 5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }(W\otimes Z)\ar[d]^{% \psi_{X{\scalebox{0.7}{\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}}M,W,Z}}\\ {\quad\quad\quad}(X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}(M\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{% \rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }W))\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{% \rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}} }Z\ar@{<-}[rr]^{\vartheta_{% \scriptscriptstyle X,M,W}\otimes\,{\rm id}_{Z}}&&((X\mbox{ \scalebox{0.75}{% \char pzd}}M)\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd% }}}} }W)\mbox{\raisebox{5.0pt}{\rotatebox{180.0}{{\scalebox{0.75}{\char pzd}}}% } }Z{\quad\quad\quad}}$ commute for all $M\in{\mathcal{M}}$, $X,Y\in{\mathcal{C}}$, and $Z,W\in{\mathcal{D}}$.
Definition 4.2. An anti Yetter-Drinfel’d (aYD) module $M$ over a left Hopf algebroid is simultaneously a left $U$-comodule and right $U$-module (with action denoted by juxtaposition) such that both underlying $A$-bimodule structures from (4.8) and (4.1) coincide, and such that action followed by coaction results into $(mu)_{(-1)}\otimes_{\scriptscriptstyle{A}}(mu)_{(0)}=u_{-}m_{(-1)}u_{+(1)}% \otimes_{\scriptscriptstyle{A}}m_{(0)}u_{+(2)},\qquad u\in U,m\in M.$ An anti Yetter-Drinfel’d contramodule is called stable if $m=m_{(0)}m_{(-1)}.$
Definition 3.1 ([R]). Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a category. A type $t$ over $\mathcal{K}$ is a class $\Omega$ equipped with a mapping $t:\Omega\to\operatorname{ob}(\mathcal{K})\times\operatorname{ob}(\mathcal{K})$ such that $\Omega^{X,Y}=t^{-1}(X,Y)$ are sets for every $X,Y\in\operatorname{ob}(\mathcal{K})$. Elements of $\Omega^{X,Y}$ are called $(X,Y)$-ary operation symbols of type $t$. Terms of type $t$ are inductively defined as follows: (1) Every $\omega\in\Omega$ is a $t(\omega)$-ary term, (2) Every morphism $f:Y\to X$ of $\mathcal{K}$ determines an $(X,Y)$-ary term $x_{f}$, (3) If $p$ is an $(X,Y)$-ary term and $q$ an $(Y,Z)$-ary term then $qp$ is an $(X,Z)$-ary term, (4) $x_{gf}=x_{g}x_{f}$, and (5) $(pq)r=p(qr)$. Equations $p=q$ of type $t$ are pairs $(p,q)$ of terms of type $t$. An equational theory of type $t$ is a class $E$ of equations of type $t$.
Definition 3.2. An algebra of type $t$ is an object $A$ of $\mathcal{K}$ equipped with mappings $\omega_{A}:A^{X}\to A^{Y}$ for every $(X,Y)$-ary operation symbol $\omega$ of $t$. Terms are interpreted in $A$ as follows: (1) $(x_{f})_{A}=A^{f}$, and (2) $(qp)_{A}=q_{A}p_{A}$. An algebra $A$ satisfies an equation $p=q$ if $p_{A}=q_{A}$. It satisfies a theory $E$ if it satisfies all equations of $E$. A homomorphism $h:A\to B$ of $t$-algebras are morphisms $h:A\to B$ such that $h^{Y}\omega_{A}=\omega_{B}h^{X}$ for every $\omega\in\Omega^{X,Y}$. $\operatorname{\bf Alg}(E)$ will denote the category of $E$-algebras and $U_{E}:\operatorname{\bf Alg}(E)\to\mathcal{K}$ will be the forgetful functor.
Definition 3. A (strict) cwf-morphism $F$ between cwfs $({\mathcal{C}},T_{\mathcal{C}})$ and $(\mathcal{D},T_{\mathcal{D}})$ consists of • A functor $F_{\mathrm{fun}}:{\mathcal{C}}\to\mathcal{D}$, preserving $1$ on the nose, that is, $F_{\mathrm{fun}}(1_{{\mathcal{C}}})=1_{\mathcal{D}}$; • A natural transformation $F_{\mathrm{nat}}:T_{\mathcal{C}}\Rightarrow(T_{\mathcal{D}}\circ F_{\mathrm{% fun}})$, preserving context comprehension on the nose (explained below). Since $F_{\mathrm{nat}}$ is a natural transformation between Fam-valued presheaves, $F_{\mathrm{nat}}$ has a component for any object $\Gamma$ of ${\mathcal{C}}$, and these components are morphisms in $\textbf{Fam}(T_{C}(\Gamma),T_{\mathcal{D}}(F_{\mathrm{fun}}(\Gamma)))$. Recall that morphisms in Fam consist of a reindexing function and a family of functions. It is convenient to denote $F_{\mathrm{fun}}$, all reindexing functions, as well as all members of the families of functions, simply by $F$. Thus we have $F(A)\in\mathrm{Ty}_{\mathcal{D}}(F(\Gamma))$ and $F(a)\in\mathrm{Tm}_{\mathcal{D}}(F(\Gamma),F(A))$, for all $\Gamma$ and $A\in\mathrm{Ty}_{\mathcal{C}}(\Gamma)$ and $a\in\mathrm{Tm}_{\mathcal{C}}(\Gamma,A)$. Naturality of $F_{\mathrm{nat}}$ amounts to preservation of substitution, i.e., for all $\gamma:\Delta\to\Gamma$ in ${\mathcal{C}}$, we have $F(A[\gamma])=F(A)[F(\gamma)]\qquad\qquad F(a[\gamma])=F(a)[F\gamma]\,.$ Last but not least, we turn to the preservation of context comprehension on the nose, and require $F(\Gamma.A)=F(\Gamma).F(A)\qquad F(\mathrm{p}_{\Gamma,A})=\mathrm{p}_{F(\Gamma% ),F(A)}\qquad F(\mathrm{q}_{\Gamma,A})=\mathrm{q}_{F(\Gamma),F(A)}\,.$ Note that the universal property implies that $F(\langle\gamma,a\rangle)=\langle F(\gamma),F(a)\rangle$. The same is true for the terminal maps: $F(\langle\rangle_{\Gamma})=\langle\rangle_{F(\Gamma)}$. (End Definition 3.)
Definition 1. Fam is a category whose objects are set-indexed families of sets, denoted as $(U_{x})_{x\in X}$. A morphism of Fam with source $(U_{x})_{x\in X}$ and target $(V_{y})_{y\in Y}$ consists of a re-indexing function $f:X\to Y$ together with a family $(g_{x})_{x\in X}$ of functions $g_{x}:U_{x}\to V_{f(x)}$.
